'''Added Art''' uses an existing piece of artwork for its canvas, just as traditional [[graffiti]] uses the wall of a building for the canvas. It is essentially the graffiti of artwork. Added Art is a merging of high and low art, using the concepts of graffiti, in a high art environment. Adding to someone else’s work has been a very common occurrence in graffiti for decades. In the urban environment, it is typically considered aggressive or antagonistic in nature,<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20090412152743/http://www.myartspace.com/blog/2009/04/street-art-defacement-appropriate-media.html ]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.myballard.com/2009/07/06/vandals-deface-bergen-place-mural/|title=» Vandals deface Bergen Place mural|date=6 July 2009|publisher=}}</ref> but also form of competition. However, it is still considered a taboo in the more established high arts, even though it has been practiced for over fifty years by stalwarts such as [[Rauschenberg]] in his ''[[Erased de Kooning Drawing]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://time4time.blogspot.com//2007/06/robert-raushenberg-erased-de-kooning.html|title=time4time|publisher=}}</ref> In more recent examples, [[Banksy]] has done several added art pieces over [[Damien Hirst]]'s "spot" painting,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artofthestate.co.uk/banksy/banksy-versus-bristol-museum-044-hirst-roller-rat.htm|title=Banksy – Hirst spot painting with roller rat|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/edcotton/2266287615/|title=Banksy/Hirst Collaboration- $1.8 million|publisher=}}</ref> and [[Mat Benote]] used an untitled work by [[Robert Morris (artist)|Robert Morris]] at the MoMA in NYC as a canvas.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.juxtapoz.com/Current/controversial-graffiti-artist-mat-benote-strikes-the-guggenheim|title=Juxtapoz Magazine – Juxtapoz Magazine|publisher=|access-date=2009-08-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090807093332/http://www.juxtapoz.com/Current/controversial-graffiti-artist-mat-benote-strikes-the-guggenheim|archive-date=2009-08-07|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref> A very interesting example was done by the [[Chapman Brothers]], who painted over sketches originally created by Adolf Hitler.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/art/news/the-art-of-adolf-hitler-with-a-little-help-from-the-chapman-brothers-836755.html |title=News &#124; UK and Worldwide News &#124; Newspaper |publisher=The Independent |date= |accessdate=2016-10-06}}</ref>
