{{For|the hobby of painting miniature figures, figurative paintings and model figures|Figure painting (hobby)}}
[[File:Golden Apple of Discord by Jacob Jordaens.jpg|thumb|350px|''The Golden Apple of Discord'' at the wedding of [[Peleus]] and [[Thetis]], [[Jacob Jordaens]], 1633, {{convert|181|x|288|cm|abbr=on}}, oil on canvas]]
<!-- [[Image:Edgar Germain Hilaire Degas 032.jpg|thumb|alt=Painting of nude woman in an 19th centurty bathtub|''Woman at her Bath'', by [[Edgar Degas]], ca. 1885.]] [[File:Whistler James Symphony in White no 1 (The White Girl) 1862.jpg|thumb|''[[Symphony in White, No. 1: The White Girl]]'' (1862) by [[James Abbott McNeill Whistler]]]]-->
A '''figure painting''' is a work of [[fine art]] in any of the [[Painting#Painting media|painting media]] with the primary subject being the human figure, whether clothed or [[Nude (art)|nude]].
Figure painting may also refer to the activity of creating such a work. The human figure has been one of the constant subjects of art since the first stone age cave paintings, and has been reinterpreted in various styles throughout history.
==Depicting figures==
Unlike [[figure drawing]]s which are usually nudes, figure paintings are often [[historical]], [[mythological]], [[allegorical]] or [[Imagination|imaginary]] depictions that may have figures in appropriate costumes. A [[portrait painting]] is a figure painting that focuses on the creation of a likeness of a particular individual or group.

The nude has been a theme in [[Western art]] since [[classical antiquity]]<ref>{{cite web| author=Sorabella, Jean|title=The Nude in Western Art and its Beginnings in Antiquity,  In Heilbrunn Timeline of Art History| location=New York| publisher=The Metropolitan Museum of Art| url=http://www.metmuseum.org/toah/hd/nuba/hd_nuba.htm|date=January 2008|accessdate=25 October 2012}}</ref> and again in the [[Renaissance]], after being largely absent during the [[Middle Ages]].<ref>{{cite web| author=Sorabella, Jean|title=The Nude in the Middle Ages and the Renaissance,  In Heilbrunn Timeline of Art History| location=New York| publisher=The Metropolitan Museum of Art| url=http://www.metmuseum.org/toah/hd/numr/hd_numr.htm|date=January 2008|accessdate=25 October 2012}}</ref>
<!-- {{quotebox|source=Willem de Kooning|quote=Flesh is the reason oil paint was invented}} -->
Oil paint historically has been the ideal media for depicting the figure. By blending and layering paint, the surface can become more like skin. "Its slow drying time and various degrees of viscosity enable the artist to achieve rich and subtle blends of color and texture, which can suggest transformations from one human substance to another."<ref>Scala, p. 1</ref> Although working from [[Model (art)|live models]] is preferred, the length of time needed to complete a painting has led most modern painters to use photographs as references at least part of the time if not for the entire work.

Figure painting is not synonymous with [[figurative art]], which may depict real objects of any kind (including humans and animals).

